Relationship Between Entities
The following table outlines the relationships between the various entities in the streaming service database schema, as defined by the provided diagram.

Source Entity	Relationship Type	Target Entity
User	One to Many	Profile
User	One to Many	Subscription
Profile	One to Many	Content
Profile	One to Many	WatchHistory
Profile	One to Many	RatingsReviews
Profile	One to Many	SearchLogs
Profile	One to Many	PlaybackSession
Content	One to Many	WatchHistory
Content	One to Many	RatingsReviews
Content	One to Many	PlaybackSession
Content	Many to Many	CastCrew
Content	One to Many	Ads
Subscription	One to Many	Content
Subscription	One to Many	PlaybackSession
RatingsReviews	One to Many	WatchHistory
RatingsReviews	One to Many	SearchLogs
PlaybackSession	One to Many	Ads

Key Relationship Details

User Centrality:  The User entity acts as the primary root, connecting to both Subscription and Profile.

Profile Activities:  The Profile entity is linked to almost all activity logs, including WatchHistory, RatingsReviews, SearchLogs, and PlaybackSessions.

Content Connections:  Content serves as the bridge between the media metadata and the user interactions (reviews, history, sessions).

Many-to-Many:  Note that Content and CastCrew share a Many-to-Many relationship, typically requiring a junction table in a physical database implementation.






